<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06004232 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06004232 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  NEW-YORK; TELEPHONE; DAMAGE; DECREASE; STOCK; TRADE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  A severed ATandamp;T phone line crippled long-distance phone service today in theNew York area, halting trading at some financial markets and delaying hundredsof airline flights in the region.;    Beginning at 9:30 a.m., many calls intoand out of the metropolitan area were met with a recorded message saying thatall circuits were busy, said a spokesman for the American Telephone andTelegraph Co. The problem also disrupted some overseas calls, the company said.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  SEVERED PHONE LINE HAMPERS TRADING  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Mercury News Staff Writer Alex Barnum contributed to this report.  </MEMO><TEXT>     Spokeswoman Marilyn Resnick said 60 percent of the calls into and out ofNew York City still were blocked as of 2 p.m. The remaining calls werererouted, she said.;    The problem was traced by the computers that runATandamp;T's phone network to an underground fiber-optic phone line in Newark, N.J.;   On Wall Street, the Commodity Exchange suspended its operations at 10:26a.m., not resuming until about three hours later. The New York MercantileExchange was closed at 10:28 a.m. and remained closed at midafternoon.;    Theoutage was disrupting phone traffic in all parts of the country, including theBay Area. Many calls to the Northeast were met with busy signals, and an ATandamp;Tspokesman said businesses with a large volume of 800 calls would beparticularly hard hit.;    In addition, the spokesman said major metropolitanareas other than those on the East Coast could experience congestion becauseof the number of calls that are being rerouted through those cities.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  New York  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910104  </PUBDATE> 